          <button class="apply-ref-btn" title="Try in Playground" onclick="window.applyRefCode && window.applyRefCode(this.closest('.ref-card').querySelector('.ref-code-data').textContent.trim())"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor" stroke="none"><polygon points="5 3 19 12 5 21 5 3"></polygon></svg></button>
        </div>
        <p class="ref-intro">Package multi-step choreographies into reusable <code>seq</code> blocks. The ultimate power move.</p>
        <div class="ref-code-wrap">
        <pre><code>seq wave(arm, angle) {'{'}
  @+0.0: $.rotate_part(part=${'${arm}'}, to=${'${angle}'}, dur=0.3)
  @+0.3: $.rotate_part(part=${'${arm}'}, to=25, dur=0.3)
{'}'}

@2.0: lily.play(wave, arm=arm_left, angle=-80)</code></pre>
        <script type="text/plain" class="ref-code-data">
scene width=800 height=400
actor lily = figure(#fad4c0, f, 😊) at (400, 200) scale 1.5

seq wave(arm, angle) {
  @+0.0: $.rotate_part(part=${arm}, to=${angle}, dur=0.3)
  @+0.3: $.rotate_part(part=${arm}, to=25, dur=0.3)
}

@1.0: lily.play(wave, arm=arm_left, angle=-80)
@2.0: lily.play(wave, arm=arm_right, angle=80)
        </script>
        </div>
        <p><code>$</code> refers to the calling actor. Times with <code>@+</code> are relative offsets from when <code>.play()</code> is triggered.</p>
